Teaching Mission Statement

The mission of the TC Beirne School of Law is to educate students in and about the law. We seek to assist you to think critically about the law and to investigate its structures, principles, policies, and values. This is achieved by engaging with you as fellow investigators in a range of critical and intellectual conversations about the law and its place in society. Our role is thus to guide you in your own intellectual journey in the law and to equip you with the necessary skills that will enable you to continue that journey long after you have left the School.

Course Aims

This course is one of several law courses offered by the Law School to business and commerce students. These courses share common objectives which may be summarised as follows:

to equip you with sufficient knowledge in relevant fields of Australian taxation law to enable you, upon graduation, to deal with business persons and legal advisers, in relation to taxation matters, in an informed and reasoned manner;

to demonstrate to you the development of legal principles through case law and statutory provisions;

to provide you with a methodology for solving legal problems based on the following steps: identifying the issue; stating the relevant principles and authorities; applying the law; and reaching a conclusion;

to inculcate in you an attitude of professionalism and an awareness of ethical standards with regard to presentation of written work; interaction with university staff; treatment of peers; and dealings with members of the professions;

to enhance your verbal communication skills by encouraging you to participate in discussion and debate of legal topics; and

to inspire you to approach the study of law with a keen and inquiring mind, and to maintain life-long interest in legal matters.
